----------------------------------------------------------------------
SCOPE OF THE BORROWING
----------------------------------------------------------------------

The following design elements originate with ojo and Joe Neeman's
blog series:

  * The *graggle* (graph + file) data structure — a directed graph of
    lines that generalises a file's linear order into a partial order
    so that pushouts always exist. Used as the package name and as
    the central type `store.Graggle`.

  * The pseudo-edge bookkeeping that bridges over deleted regions
    so the live subgraph stays connected after tombstoning.

  * The patch-with-placeholder-hashes construction: changes are
    hashed with self-references replaced by a sentinel placeholder,
    then the placeholders are rewritten to the resulting patch hash.
    See `patch.NewPatch` and the comment at `patch.go:159`.

  * The apply / unapply / reapply round-trip test pattern used in
    the property-based test suite. See `store/property_test.go:386`.

The Go implementation is an independent re-implementation guided by
the blog series, not a line-by-line port of ojo's Rust source. No
ojo code was copied verbatim. Several local design choices diverge
from ojo and from the upstream `hackathon_2026` snapshot; these are
flagged inline with `VENDOR DEVIATION:` comments — currently the
BLAKE3 hash function (versus crypto/sha256), idempotent
`store.Graggle.DeleteNode`, the de-fixup step in
`patch.Patch.ComputeHash`, and the hex `MarshalText` / `UnmarshalText`
on `types.PatchHash`.

----------------------------------------------------------------------
RELATIONSHIP TO THE COMPANION PIJUL PACKAGE
----------------------------------------------------------------------

The sibling package `public/algebraicarch/pushout/pijul/` wraps the
Pijul VCS (a production patch-theory VCS that ojo prototypes ideas
for) as a four-actor demo. It defines a `BackendI`/`RepoI` seam with
two realisations: `pijulTextBackend` shells out to a real `pijul`
binary; `pijulPushoutBackend` uses the graggle subtree directly
without invoking an external binary. Pijul itself is GPL-2.0 and is
not redistributed by boxer — only invoked at runtime when the text
backend is selected.

See `public/algebraicarch/pushout/pijul/EXPLANATION.md` for the
broader conceptual lineage (Mimram & Di Giusto 2013, Darcs, Pijul,
ojo) and for the reasons behind the Graph Context Ambiguity and the
two-backend split.
